I printed the 590956 Spool Mount and was very pleased until I tried to use it. It immediately spread apart, dropping the spool of filament. So, I created these clips to secure the Spool Mount. They attach by dropping through the open web in the Spool Mount and securing with a couple 4" wire ties. I designed these for use with 65mm wide filament spools, and included a hole in the center of the front clip as a filament guide. Enjoy!  
UPDATE 01-01-15: I remixed this item to include an adjustable fan (or anything?) mount! See the instructions for build parts, and check out the images for dimensions.

The ones I use are for 65mm wide spools. They were printed in PLA at 0.3mm layer height with a 0.4mm nozzle at 200C on a 50C heated bed.  They are attached using four 4" wire ties.  
UPDATE 01-01-15: The remixed version with the fan brackets needs a few bits to assemble: M3x12 screws and nuts x4 and whatever hardware you want to use to mount your fan. This will fit most fans - I am using a fairly large, 100mm fan to cool the entire print bed without ducting getting in the way! Works like a charm during printing and even cools the bed to release the parts without scraping!

title: Local Motors Strati 3D printed car - modified for rolling wheels and detail

description.text:
I really enjoy the model of the Local Motors Strati 3D printed car that is posted on Thingiverse, but I wanted to make it simultaneously more similar to the real car, and with rolling wheels.  
Working off the original files, I started from the individual files and scaled them to 1/20 scale. For some reason 1/10 was way too big for my printer. The original separate body file seems to be finer and more detailed, so this gives you improved quality.  
Next I cut out holes in the body so that an axle will pass through.  
I rebuilt the suspension pivots and struts to be more robust, and also to allow room for a rotating wheel.  
The windshield is broken out as a separate part so you can make it in clear plastic if available.  (I used an Objet Connex printer for this)  
Last but not least, I modeled from scratch a wheel that looks more like the real one that was shown. The tires are separate, so you can print them in flexible filament/elastomer/another color if you so desire.

Here's how to print it.  
Print two each of the suspension pivot (L and R versions). The axle hole is offset towards the REAR of the car. Print 4x suspension struts. Print one each of the roll bar, battery, motor, steering wheel and windshield.  
Print the body.  
Print 4x wheel using support. Print 4x tires. The "objet" version of the tire is for an Objet Connex printer which can print with rubber-like materials.  
You will need a 3mm or so steel rod for the axles. Cut it into two 81mm lengths.  
To assemble, glue a strut into the strut hole in the top of the wheel arch. Next glue the appropriate suspension pivot in place, and use a drop of glue to hold the other end of the strut into the top of the suspension arm. Do this for all the wheels.  
Fit the tires to the wheels.  
Glue the battery box in place. Glue the motor in place. Thread an axle through to make sure the motor is correctly placed.   
Glue the wheels to the end of the axles.  
Glue the steering wheel to a small piece of rod, or just straight to the dashboard. Attach the roll bar and windshield. Color in the lights with a silver marker if you want.

description.text:
These legs are a light alternative to the stock landing gear.  They are great for landing in snow or long grass.  They easily snap on and off and no screws or copter mods are required.  The snap on clamps are tapered so that the legs protrude down perfectly straight.  
If you happen to crash into a tall tree, the gear will probably come off as the copter falls to the ground so your copter won't get stuck 80 feet up in the tree.  
If you have a camera, this gear will protect from a hard vertical landing, but probably not an uncontrolled horizontal landing.  If you are new to flying, you could use these as well as the stock gear to protect your camera.

1) Print the arm clamp (4 at a time)
2) Print the foot (4 at a time)
3) Cut a piece of 4mm carbon rod to whatever length you want. I am using 10 cm now
4) Clean up the holes with a 4mm or 5/32 drill if needed.
5) Tap the rods into the holes gently. You might want to taper the carbon rod a bit with a file to make it simpler

title: Printed jig for metal CNC bearing

description.text: It's important to have a well supported linear rail system if you ever intend to cut through thick metal using your CNC mill. It's unfortunate that professionally made bearings can be so pricey. Several makers in the past have come up with great ways to machine their own homemade railing from the 1/2" steel rods you find at hardware stores, but so far no one has yet attempted to make their own bearings, at least to my knowledge. I've designed a jig you can print out in order to do so. The jig can be wrapped around a 1" aluminum cube, allowing guide holes to be drilled for the screws and bushing. To make an entire CNC machine, you'll need 12 of these. This translates to approximately 1 foot of 1" aluminum bar stock. You can find this available on amazon for less than the cost of a single 4 pack of bearings. video

Download and print bearing-jig.stl. Wrap the jig around a 1" (30mm) aluminum cube. You can cut such a cube from 1"x1" (30m x30mm) aluminum bar stock. It not important how long you cut the block, so long as the sides are orthogonal to one another and can rest soundly in the jig. With the jig in place, drill a set of five 1-3mm holes to match the holes you see on the jig. Switch out your drill bit and enlarge these to 4mm. Use an M5 or 10-32 tap to thread the four holes on the bottom of the piece. These will allow you to connect the bearings to a board. Enlarge the remaining hole to 1/2" (12mm) in size. You may need to use several drill bits to accomplish this. After the hole is drilled, use a saw to remove a 3/8" (10mm) clearing in the thin wall that you created while drilling. File the walls in and around the hole as needed until the bearing is able to slide easily through a 1/2" supported linear rail.

Rosette for pipes for waterworks.
All the rosettes that I can get in the stores are ugly. So I needed a custom one. Useless fact:
I used a cylinder with variable number of sides for the hole. I needed this to fit to a hexagonal nut. But OpenScad uses the center-to-tip size for diameter. Usually hex (and square) sizes are side-to-side. So I had to divide the radius by cos(180/NumberOfSidesForHole). Therefore this works for square, hexagonal, 8-sides 12 sided and round holes. I'm proud of myself, but noone will ever notice the true beauty of it.

title: Custom bins for X-Wing miniatures ships
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
These are drop in bins for the Stanley "Sortimo" style case. I have started modeling the ships in my collection and will continue as I add more. The goal is to make secure bins while maximizing space so that as many ships as possible can fit in the case. I have so far stuck with the medium compartment size, but may move to the large or custom sizes as the need arises. Feedback is welcome, but ship requests likely won't be honored unless I own the ship. If you use these please post your makes and thoughts. I would love to see these in your collection! This is a work in progress because I will be adding more, but the ones that are already added are pretty much final. It took me about 8 prints to get the x-wing right. This is a exhaustive process because I want them to fit securely with little room to move around, but they need to be easily removable. Finding that sweet spot has been challenging on the more complex models. Partially inspired by thing 368666, except mine are specifically designed for the Stanley cases. Also inspired by BoardGameGeek user xBino. I have started a thread over on BGG found here... http://boardgamegeek.com/thread/1289088/3d-printed-custom-bins-stanley-storage-box The cases available so far are as follows... Small Bin, 1 Tie Fighter
Medium Bin, 2 Tie Fighters
Medium Bin, 2 Tie Interceptors
Medium Bin, 2 X-wings, or 2 Z-95 Head Hunters, or Mix and Match.
Medium Bin, 3 A-Wings
Medium Bin, 1 B-Wing
Medium Bin, 1 Y-Wing
Small Bin, 1 E-Wing
Medium, 4 Tie Advanced
Medium, 3 Tie Bombers
Medium, 2 Tie Bombers, 1 Tie Advanced
Medium, 1 Tie Bombers, 2 Tie Advanced
Medium, 1 Tie Defender

Buy a Stanley Organizer, amazon link below. You may be able to also find at your local hardware store (Home Depot, etc) http://www.amazon.com/Stanley-25-Removable-Compartment-Professional-Organizer/dp/B00005QWYF/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1419298105&sr=8-1&keywords=sortimo Print out the bins and enjoy.
I use .3mm Layer height with 10% infill, normal shells on a solidoodle 4. I have added a new file "TieFighterV2TestSlug.STL" which is for doing test prints so that you can tweak the settings for your setup without wasting too much time or material.

here is a Python script that will execute a batch series of OpenSCAD command lines driven from a .csv file. You can use it to generate a set of images, a set of .STLs or whatever formats are now or future supported. It uses OpenSCAD's -D capability to populate variables on the command line. Since OpenSCAD determines the output format from the extension of the output filename, that is driven from the .csv as well. The .CSV would would like this:
FILE,ARGS,able, baker, charlie
"test1.png","--render --projection=o",10,20,30
"test2.stl",,20,30,40
"test3.stl",,30,40,50 for an OpenSCAD file like this:
able = 10;
baker= 10;
charlie = 10;
cube([able,baker,charlie]); on Debian, the command
python3 openscad_batch.py -x params.csv test.scad
would generate (and optionally execute if the -x was missing,) a series of command lines like this:

  • openscad --render --projection=o -D "baker=20" -D "able=10" -D "charlie=30" -o test1.png test.scad

  • openscad -D "baker=30" -D "able=20" -D "charlie=40" -o test2.stl test.scad

  • openscad -D "baker=40" -D "able=30" -D "charlie=50" -o test3.stl test.scad
    • Notes:
  • it's Python 3 (sorry, but I've moved on. 3 is the future.)
  • it needs a recent version of OpenSCAD to be able to do things like render (see OpenSCAD docs for a list of which command line switches each version of OpenSCAD supports.
  • call it with -h to get instructions (you can also read them in the source below
  • I've tested on Windows 8.1 and Debian 64 bit
    • Here's the help it generates:

usage: openscad_batch.py [-h] [-x] CSV OPENSCAD_FILE Run OpenSCAD repeatedly with parameters driven from a .csv file. ---------- USAGE NOTES ---------------- * First _row_ of .csv contains paramter names (i.e. OpenSCAD constants) NOTE: do not enclose parameter names in quotes. * First _column_ of first _row_ must be named FILE. * First _column_ of subsequent rows must contain output file name for that row's values and be in double quotes (e.g. "cube1.stl") * Second _column_ of first _row_ must be named ARGS * Second _column_ of subsequent rows must contain OpenSCAD cmd line args for that file output or be empty (e.g. ,"--render", for a .png output or ,, for a line with no args) * String values in subsequent rows must be enclosed in double quotes. * OpenSCAD executable must be in the PATH positional arguments: CSV location of .csv file containing params OPENSCAD_FILE name of OpenSCAD file (without args) optional arguments: -h, --help show this help message and exit -x Don't execute command line (just send output to console) EXAMPLE COMMANDS: c:python34python openscad_batch.py params.csv cubeout.scad python openscad_batch.py -x params.csv cubeout.scad (linux) python3 openscad_batch.py params.csv cubeout.scad EXAMPLE .CSV FILE: FILE,ARGS,able,baker,charlie "cube1.png","--render",10,20,30 "cube2.stl",,20,30,40 "cube3.stl",,30,40,50 works with .scad file: able = 10; baker= 10; charlie = 10; cube([able,baker,charlie]);

This is a fully functional set of pliers that prints in only one piece. They work pretty well and cannot be disassembled unless they are broken.
One cool thing about the design is that it used only 10 boolean operations to make the entire model. I was going through a box of old prints and I came across a pair of pliers. It was one of my first prints, and it didn't work very well. It was not the design, just my settings at the time. Nevertheless, rather than printing a new pair of the same pliers I decided to revamp them by making them print in place. It's more of a novelty than anything useful, but it was a fun design challenge :) I was inspired by the printed pliers (designed by russrobot) and all of emmett's print in place designs.

I would recommend the V2 file because it looks a little better, but it also has a tighter tolerance (800 microns), so it may not work as well on some printers. I am using a Solidoodle 2 Pro and the print came out almost perfectly for me. If you are having trouble with the V2 file try the V1. If it works than your tolerances are not tight enough to successfully print the V2. I find that the design prints best on it's side, the way that it is oriented in the .STL file. I would recommend the MakerBot standard layer height (200 microns). The infill should be no less than 15%. I print with two shells and two bottom/top layers. I have only printed this model in PLA, but I don't see a reason that it wouldn't work with ABS. Once the print is done, simply use a sharp blade to wedge in between the two halfs on the tip and the base and snap them apart gently. This is a video of how to prepare them. http://youtu.be/fd35CpxsiBk

title: Holiday Ornament Remix with Failed Prints from Screwless Heart Gear

description.text:
We printed a few Screwless Gear Hearts, but some prints didn't quite make it to the end. In one case our plastic ran out before the print completed and another just had a regular printing glitch. We decided to see what we could come up with using the leftover print parts and got some fun Holiday Ornaments for our effort. You can read a bit more here:
https://wordpress.com/post/78513574/78

If your print makes it about 2/3 of the way through then you can clean the pieces with a sharp chisel so that the top and bottom faces are flat. Put the pin clips in the top piece, stack another piece below as a the bottom and super glue them together. We added some pressure using a clamp while the glue set up. We think that you could use Emmett's original stl files for heart gears 2 & 4 with the Heartpins files if you started off with the intent to print these parts for ornaments, but seriously - this is just a way to reuse failed parts. We put the .stl files for those three parts in this remix post so you can find them easily, but we didn't actually make changes to Emmett's design - so give attribution to him!!!

comments.text:
sculptris
use the brush function.(with a custom brush image)
make a jpg (black background, white 'brush') In the shape you want to paint.
load the brush and enable. (smaller works better for me)
I prefer to use the brush in airbrush off, clay with strength set high.
but the preferences are easily adjusted.
The brush can be finicky, it is important to reorient the model
to get the brush to paint evenly.
once you get the hang of it, it is easy.
one other "gotcha", if using symmetry, I find the brush

description.text:
Well, I decided that none of the current iPhone 4 cases available will protect my soon-to-be-received Verizon iPhone adequately, so I'm designing my own case. To do that, though, I had to download the Apple PDF of the technical drawings of the iPhone 4. That is NOT a friendly format for ANY CAD program, so I decided that I would make it more friendly.
FYI: These dimensions may not be entirely accurate. I made most of the holes are larger than the ports they surround because that's the only way making a case would work. I modeled this from the Verizon iPhone's specs so it may not work for AT&T users, but I think I compensated enough (it's really only a difference in the positioning of the mute switch).
DISCLAIMER: Most of the holes (the things sticking out in the STL) are bigger than the features they represent to help with case design--this is not really meant to be a model of an iPhone for illustrative purposes.

The case negative is meant to be subtracted from a block of whatever shape you want to properly generate all the case holes and cutouts. This could also be used to make holders, docks, etc.
The Alibre file can be used to make your own case negative.

title: Christmas Tree - Your own personal mini 3D printed Christmas tree with coloured decorations!

description.text:
4 part slot together Christmas tree plus a star for the top which prints separately so you can use a different colour... natural PLA looks great for a star.   
Pause the print at 3mm (approx. 97% with no raft) to change colour which adds the decorations.   
The star is designed with a small amount of support that needs to be removed. This lets the stem protrude into the top of the tree to lightly secure it so it will stay in place.   
Note: This tree has 8 sides in total so is more complex than other trees using a similar slot together method.

On a Replicator 2 print without Raft and no Support either. The tree prints well with 3 shells / 20% fill and 0.20mm resolution. The star is best printed "with" Raft and prints well with 3 shells and 50% fill to make it almost solid. Z-Pause build at 3mm (approx. 97% without Raft) and change the colour to add coloured decorations. Print the star separately. Natural PLA looks great due to its shiny translucent appearance. There is a small amount of designed in support on the base of the star that should be easy to remove. This exposes a longer centre stem that protrudes beyond the lower points of the star. This tem will help slot it securely into the top of the tree (assuming printer is printing accurately) Notes:
(1) Recommend levelling build plate before starting this print due to some details on the underside that can come away during the first layer if not well levelled. If you choose to use Raft the filament change point will need to be adjusted to compensate for the Raft thickness (usually about 1.25mm but varies by machine)

This is a mostly 3D printable sumo bot. It is going to be competing in the Science Olympiad sumo bot event. So far, the major vitamins we used are as follows...

We needed to add about 800grams to the bot to bring it up to the maximum 2kg weight limit. Once we were at 2kg it pushed two textbooks easy, which total about 5kg. We will be competing this Saturday with it.
    • Previous years we either used completely Vex, or hand fabricated chassis using steel corner brackets and aluminum plate. This year we were able to 3D print the majority of the parts, which made it much easier. For example, previous years we were limited in the tire types we were able to use, but now we were able to make a fully integrated hub and drive coupler. Just a note about the files, they are not at all parametric. I drew a picture in my head with the measurements and wrote the code. This is a VESA mount (100mm) that is meant to secure a Raspberry Pi housed in the milled aluminum enclosure from adafruit.

Successfully printed on a Replicator 2 with fill=50%, shells=1, layer size=0.125mm
You'll need the MScrew.scad file for OpenSCAD if you want to modify this design. You can find it here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:56492 The raspberries enclosure is mounted to the adapter with three M3x6? mm screws. I couldn't successfully print those, but the four M4x10mm screws needed to attach the adapter to the back of your monitor were successfully printed. This is a 100mm vesa adapter by the way. I suggest using blue tape on the build platform. I printed directly to the plate and the model began breaking loose from the plate. I'd suggest a fairly high resolution as the nuts on the top have threads. You can print this in two pieces if you look at the .scad file. At the bottom you can change what prints. The file also includes some spacers (not printed by default) if you need them between the enclosure and the adapter (depends on how long your screws are). So using the .scad file you could elect a low-res fast print for the flat base, then just print the nuts using a higher resolution after the base plate has finished. I just did it in one go with the settings mentioned above. Lastly, if you look closely at the picture you'll see an extra 'reference' mounting hole on the left top arm that is partly visible. It should have lined up with that screw on the aluminum case. It didn't and I don't know why, nevertheless I measured the offset and hardcoded a 'slide this to the left 5mm' fix. So when printed the pi should be a bit more centered. (and those holes aren't needed and don't need to be printed. But they're hidden and will help me keep things in alignment for now.
